## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException cleanup** | `catch` block | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | catch block | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| **Thread.Abort()** | `Stop()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
                token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint before processing
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — loop condition handles exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, the thread is truly stuck.
        // Unlike Thread.Abort, there is NO way to force-kill it in .NET 8.
        // See "Uncooperative code" pitfall below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`**
The caller signals cancellation; the worker checks cooperatively. Cancellation is *not* immediate — it only takes effect at the next checkpoint.

**2. `ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`**
The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated exceptions.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed entirely**
Not needed. The loop condition `!token.IsCancellationRequested` controls whether to continue. After catching the exception, the loop naturally exits on the next iteration.

**4. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(TimeSpan)`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to finish instead of blindly sleeping and re-checking.

**5. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token**
This is the most critical change. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it **must** observe the token or cancellation will stall:

```csharp
// Before — blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
var item = _queue.Take();

// After — wakes up immediately when cancelled
var item = _queue.Take(token);  // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
```

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing the token to blocking calls** | `GetNextItem()` may block forever. Cancellation only works if the blocking call observes the token. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always implement `IDisposable`. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If code can't be modified to check the token (e.g., native call), move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in .NET 8. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level loop. Let it propagate through intermediate methods. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at checkpoints. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations. |
